      "content": {
        "headerTitle": "Common Gambling Fallacies",
        "layout": "concept-full",
        "layoutData": {
          "title": "Mistaken Beliefs About Gambling",
          "paragraphs": [
            "The mistaken belief that if an event happens frequently, it will happen less frequently in the future. Reality: Each independent event has the same probability.",
            "Believing that a person who has experienced success will continue to succeed. Reality: Past wins don't affect future outcomes in games of chance.",
            "In 1913, gamblers lost millions betting against black when it came up 26 times in a rowâ€”thinking red was \"due.\" Reality: Each spin was still 50/50.",
            "In truly independent events, each outcome is unaffected by previous results. The roulette wheel has no memory, the dice don't know what they rolled before."
          ],
          "bulletPoints": []
        }
      }
